  <article class="prose">
    <span class="eyebrow">Booklet · Sullivan and Bird · 2025</span>
    <h1>Schools of the Republic</h1>
    <p class="kicker"><em>The Fiduciary Inheritance of the Common Schools, 1785–2026.</em> Sullivan and Bird, 2025. Substrate v1.3. Nine chapters of synthesis drawing on the Library's per-state record.</p>

    <p>
      <em>Schools of the Republic</em> is the synthesizing analytic treatment
      of America's longest-running fiduciary experiment — the school-land
      trusts created beginning with the 1785 Land Ordinance and extended
      through every state admission from Ohio to Hawaii. The book traces how
      the trusts were designed, how they have drifted, and what design
      principles their successor structures will need.
    </p>

    <p>
      The per-state evidentiary record this synthesis draws on lives in
      America's School Trust Library — in its
      <a href="/atlas/">Atlas</a>, its <a href="/map-room/">Map Room</a>, and
      its <a href="/counting/">Counting House</a>, where it remains alive and
      continues to be added to. The book draws on that record without
      duplicating it.
    </p>

    <h2>The throughline — Prologue, six era chapters, comparative pass, conclusion</h2>
    <p>Nine chapters tracing the school-trust compact from the 1785 Land Ordinance through admission-era doublings, the school clause, fiduciary breach, the captured-Attorney-General enforcement architecture, and the constituency that remedies it.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/reading/prologue/">Prologue: Before the Section Lines</a></li>
      <li><a href="/reading/founding-floor/">Chapter 1: The Founding Floor</a></li>
      <li><a href="/reading/statehood-without-federal-floor/">Chapter 2: Statehood Without the Federal Floor</a></li>
      <li><a href="/reading/northwest-ordinance-template/">Chapter 3: The Northwest Ordinance Template</a></li>
      <li><a href="/reading/antebellum-doubling/">Chapter 4: The Antebellum Doubling</a></li>
      <li><a href="/reading/reconstruction-western-stack/">Chapter 5: Reconstruction and the Western Stack</a></li>
      <li><a href="/reading/twentieth-century-high-water-mark/">Chapter 6: The Twentieth-Century High-Water Mark and Two Outliers</a></li>
      <li><a href="/reading/comparative-atlas/">Chapter 7: Comparative Atlas</a></li>
      <li><a href="/reading/enforcement-beneficiary-cannot-sue/">Chapter 8: Enforcement when the Beneficiary Cannot Sue — The Captured-AG Architecture and the Eighth Anchor</a></li>
      <li><a href="/reading/conclusion/">Chapter 9: Conclusion — Architecture, Constituency, and the Recovery That Is Possible</a></li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The per-state record lives in the Library</h2>
    <p>
      The per-state dossiers — constitutional architecture, admission-act
      provisions, permanent fund corpus, federal grant acreage, and current
      trust-integrity status — live in the Library's
      <a href="/atlas/">Atlas</a>, with state cohort pages organized by era
      under <a href="/atlas/">/atlas/</a>. The same record surfaces in the
      <a href="/map-room/">Map Room</a> for transparency posture and the
      <a href="/counting/">Counting House</a> for fund balances and audit
      disclosure.
    </p>

    <hr class="archival-divider">

    <p>This booklet is the synthesis. The <a href="/atlas/">Atlas</a>, the <a href="/counting/">Counting House</a>, and the <a href="/reading/sacred-compact-prologue/">Sacred Compact</a> white paper draw on the same evidentiary substrate.</p>
